spans.text: of Men Original , Why does thy Head upon thy Bosom fall
Mortals all by our disposes move
Since Death is natural to all are born , Why dost thou languish thus , why dost thou mourn
Primitive offence , Hymen , for Sin I own , But ah , why should she Perish that had none
it be due upon her Wedding-day
dash their sweetest draughts of Life with woe
Yet spite of all their Graces
If these could not thy Avarice overcome
the mighty sum , Her graceful Modesty
as the other great ; And then for Patience , and blessed

Yet born to die , Not only die , but in her blooming Age , To feel the Curse of thy extremest Rage , A double Death did her dear Life pursue , Of Beauty first , and then of Nature too , Vile Schelliton that wouldst not Pity show , But where no Flesh is , how should Pity grow
With pointed Beams had shot thee to the Soul

Even Death had else been fooled into desire , Pity had warmed my Breast to let her live , And Female Charms had purchased a Reprieve , Had not resenting Ghosts over whom I Reign , All murmuring at a thought so strange , so vain , Declared in the Grand Council of my State , Pity was fit for any thing but Fate
a thought so strange , so vain , Declared in the Grand Council of my State , Pity was fit for any thing but Fate
Pity was fit for any thing but Fate
more fit for any thing than Love
Where harmless Lovers pretty Garlands wove
Aspatia's hapless Fate each Breast shall sway , Aspatia's storey
Aspatia's hapless Fate each Breast shall sway , Aspatia's storey
from the Deity Hymen has power to alter Fate's decree , Of this great wrong he'll never cease to complain , Nor ever tie the genial Knot again
